Once with a half tone dither and once with no dither and a b/w threshold of 90 or so. Walls are laser engraved XLPE foam. It is laser engraved with a 40w laser at 100% speed and 75% power using a simple dither @250 DPI. description.text: I dropped my charger and broke the button.  I had carved down a wooden dowel to make a replacement but it never worked well.  So spent a few minutes with my calipers and openSCAD and whipped this up.  Fits perfect and doesn't fall out on mine!

Printer Brand:

RepRap

FolgerTech 2020 Prusa i3

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

.01mm

Infill:

N/A

Notes: I printed this at .01mm to try get as much of the rounded top as I could, I'd suggest printing at least 4 at once even if you don't need that many or plating it up with some other pieces since printing one by itself it doesn't have time to cool between layers and will get sloppy. I used 3 perimeters for strength and infill didn't really matter. The button is slightly tapered which should keep it from falling out, and the hole the pushbutton goes into is slightly tapered as well which allows it to grip the button quite well.

Grabbed my calipers and measured one of the original buttons for OD and length as well as depth of the button hole.  Then measured the switch to size the width/taper of the hole in the bottom.  The openSCAD file is pretty ugly because I just tossed this together at 1AM while waiting on my laundry..but it works :D

Lattice models are attractive, useful teaching tools and not easy to construct. The diamond lattice is a traditional example. Diamond crystallizes to form a cubic cell in which each carbon atom forms four bonds. The diamond lattice has octahedral symmetry and the view into each of the 12 edges of the cell is the same. The Naval Research Laboratory in Washington has long had a Division for the Structure of Matter. NRL hosts a large collection of crystal lattice structures.
Note : The NRL no longer hosts these pages - new links below -
https://homepage.univie.ac.at/michael.leitner/lattice/spcgrp/index.html
On one of their web pages I found a downloadable set of coordinates for the diamond unit cell.
https://homepage.univie.ac.at/michael.leitner/lattice/struk/a4.html
As in "Buckyballs" I used a fortran program to make openSCAD module calls. Expand_diamond.f takes the unit cell coordinates of diamond, expands them to a 27 cell cube, and outputs the required calls. I was surprised at how well the model printed. I recently installed a MK7 extruder which seems to produce cleaner results. There were 276 atoms in the first prints and all but four printed perfectly. Four atoms, two at each of two edges, slanted downwards and did not print well. I removed them from the model and began to get perfect prints. The picture displays three of the models. The smaller version in the center shows the build surface; the atoms detached from the raft have marks on their surfaces. The larger models are about 65 mm on a side; the one on the right shows a view into an edge. The fortran program used to generate the diamond openSCAD module calls, expand_diamond.f, is below as are the openSCAD program and the stl output that printed best.

I printed all my models using rafts.  The stl file is oriented so that 23 atoms touch the build surface.  The software makes 23 little pads which easily pop off the completed print to give a nice sturdy model.  On examining a finished print it will be obvious where the missing atoms should go.
I've made several attempts to print more open models by decreasing the size of the carbon atoms but the results were not very good.  If you want to try to print such a model you can, for example, change the atomic radius in the openSCAD atom calls from .5 to .3 and compile and render the code.  It takes about 7 hours to render on my machine.

    • Step two - Designing your cube Draw a cube on your graph paper ( assuming your graph paper is 4 squares to an inch ) the square you draw should have 16 squares on each face each square .5'' as shown in the drawing below. after drawing your cube we will begin making it a puzzle in the next step Step 3 - Breaking down your cube Once you've drawing you cube you should understand that a 4x4 cube has 64 squares in total. The rule we're going by in this puzzle is why each puzzle should be unique to the creator it has to fit into a set of rules. Rules.

description.text: I'm installing magnetic child locks on all the cabinets and drawers in the house to keep my kid out of things. I've been using the Safety 1st brand locks and have been happy with them, but the kits really don't come with enough keys and it seems like there's never one around when you need to get into a drawer. So I ordered some magnets from ebay and designed some housings to make my own keys. Each key requires two 25mm x 2mm neodymium magnets Thanks to the rare earth magnets, these keys are actually a little stronger and seem to work better than the originals. They also double as excellent fridge magnets :) Note: I've only tested these keys with the Safety 1st locks, but these keys should work with any brand of lock with a similar design, just make sure the polarity of your magnets matches the ones on your original key.

Align your magnets You'll need to check to make sure that the polarity on your magnets is aligned the right way to operate your locks. The easiest way to do this is to make sure that the bottom of your original key and the bottom of your new key repel each other. If the magnets try to stick together then you'll need to flip the magnets in your new key around 180* Test fitting the magnets Your magnets should repel the original key Glue in the magnets Put a few drops of superglue around the base of the key to make sure the magnets won't rattle around inside once the key is glued together. Then drop in the magnets in place making sure to keep the magnets oriented the right way. Put a few drops of glue in the base just to make sure the magnet won't rattle around at all Glue your key together Now that your magnets are oriented the right way, it's time to glue the two halves of your key together. Run a thin bead of glue around the rim of the key base, and also put a drop of glue into each hole in the top of the key. Then line the holes up with the pins in the base of the key and press the two halves together. Hold the key together for 15-30 seconds to give the glue time to set. description.text:
I designed these to hold a Polycarbonate Sheet (Lexan) on a Robo3d Printer heated bed.
This stuff works awesome with no adhesives. I use only ABS and run the bed temp at 40c. You will get 100+ prints off of one $8 sheet.  
They may fit other printers as well. The sheet size is I bought comes from Home Depot and is 11x14x.093; you have to cut one inch off one side of the Sheet to make it fit the Robo3d printer.
Print 4 of the large ones and two of the small ones. 
The four large ones goes on each end of the build area (2 on each end)
The 2 small ones go midway on the build area on the sides. They are small enough to clear the bearing screws.
You could use all small ones if you had a 10x15 sheet cut (the actual size of the bed)

You will also want to edit your startup Gcode for a polycarbonate sheet to autolevel BEFORE you heat the nozzle. Otherwise the hot end will dig into the build plate. Here is the code I use: G28 ; home all axes
G1 Z5 F5000 ; lift Z by 5mm
M565 Z-1 ; set the offset for auto-leveling mechanism
G29 ; run auto-level
G1 Z5 F5000 ; lift Z by 5mm
M140 S[bed0_temperature] ; Set Bed Temperature
M190 S[bed0_temperature] ; Wait for Bed Temperature
M104 S[extruder0_temperature] T0 ; set extruder temperature .
M109 S[extruder0_temperature] T0 ; set extruder temperature and wait for temp
G92 E0 ; set extruder distance at zero
G92 E0 ; reset extruder distance to zero

description.text:
I made a new bracket because I wanted a split design; it means less long full surfaces and so less bowing, as well as a bit more tolerance as it does not depend on the cross-bar being the correct width and not shrinking.
It is a little tough to get the screws in, but computer screws usually have hexagonal heads, so it is quite easy to use pliers if it is too tough with fingers.
As always, I recommend testing the holes with the screws first, and if it is too difficult, pre-drill your holes by spinning the bit fast in reverse and using the heat to smooth out the holes.
I only made it with the side-screw holes, I will be making more with the under-mount and dual side and under mount options. The current versions are side-mount only (requires no supports), and side mount with an under-bracket to hold it up (you can use less screws), but it requires supports in the print.

description.text: During long print sessions I was having issues with my extruder motor overheating, resulting in the filament melting at the drive gear.  I checked around thingiverse and, while there were many types of fan mounts, I didn't see one that worked for me.  I needed the fan to be elevated so it was oriented properly to blow across the heatsink that I had attached to the extruder motor.  (see pictures).  This mount works with a 60mm fan and can be mounted with either M3 screws and nuts or zip ties. I also added a filament guide to the side of the mount.
Notes: printed on a printbot simple makers edition. print settings will vary alot depending on your filament and printer.

I tried loosening the screws that hold the acrylic panel on the front of the extruder, but it didn't solve the problem, so I scanned and traced the panel and created this spacer, then laser cut two copies in heavy paper. It seems to have fixed the problem, at least for now. I might also try a dry lubricant in the channel just in case. Raise3D is working on a v2 extruder which will presumably fix this problem, among others.
The SVG was exported from Adobe Illustrator. In some programs (e.g., CorelDraw), the result may need to be scaled by a factor of 1.333.

Audiences: Kids, junior high, high school. Steps: This project was wrapped around the idea that some times the best way to learn about something or to get interested in something is to get involved in int or even just to interact with it. This project is a simplified view of the world missing some islands here and there but it gets to the point of general learning tool. Results: This project was developed as a tool to draw kids attention and we found out it really serves its purpose, you can not only teach the pangean part of history but also the historical advance and arrangement of tectonic plates as it is today.

description.text:
I designed this part to adapt the spools I purchased from Makerbot to rotate freely on a 1" piece of conduit. This is not a ball type bearing, but functions quite well as a bearing by interfacing two hard surfaces (ABS and metal in my case)through a knife edge.
I found that when I simply hung the spools on the 1" conduit they hung off-axis and the Stepstruder did not have the torque to rotate the eccentrically mounted spool. Simply adding this adapter to re-center the spool solved the problem and it feeds beautifully.
Originally I just built the adapter, but I found on long builds that the spool tended to "walk" off. I added an end piece to hold the spool on and used a couple of small screws I had available to fasten it in place.
The parts are designed to minimize the amount of ABS used. All walls are designed to be 0.125" and I cut a number of holes out of the hold piece simply to reduce waste.
The picture makes the adapter look like a big fat cylinder, but in fact only the ends are actually 1" internal diameter (ID). There is a small 45 degree solid to create the adaptation from 1" ID to the outside diameter so that it only contacts the conduit in two small knife-edge places.

I designed these parts to print raftlessly and had no issue printing them out perfectly on a Thing-O-Matic with Automated Build Platform with no raft.
The end piece does have holes for the screws, however the adapter does not. I did that so you could use whatever screws you had available. The easiest thing is to drill small holes, but since you are screwing into a part that is honeycombed you could force a reasonably sharp screw or use a soldering iron.

title: Probe sensor for Dagoma Dicovery200 3D printer

description.text:
Le palpeur est basé sur un microswitch de souris d'ordinateur
Le doigt est libéré et descend lors du homing X, pas besoin de gcode supplémentaire pour cela.
Après le homing X,Y et Z un mouvement en Z relève le doigt et réarme le capteur pour une autre utilisation. Ce mouvement nécessite du gcode supplémentaire pour baisser la tête.
2 possibilités :
  • Coller une pièce de monnaie ou une pile bouton, qui sera la zone de contact pour le réarmement (2 ou 3 mm d'épaisseur)
  • En positionnant la tête en dehors du plateau, cela permet de descendre la buse en dessous de Z0 et le plateau soulève le doigt
    • Pour construire le palpeur, on a besoin de :
  • Un microswitch de souris d'ordinateur
  • Un rayon e vélo diamètre 2mm coupé à 75mm, garder la partie filetée pour fixer la tête
  • Un ressort de stylo bic
  • Un domino pour maintenir le ressort sur le rayon
  • Du scotch double face pour coller le baton d'armement (bout de plastique qui appuie sur le levier)
  • Un morceau de mousse pour faire ressort sous le levier
    • This is a probe sensor for the Dagoma Discovery 200 3D printer
    it come in place of the inductive sensor and does not need power supply. It is based on simple mouse microswitch. The dowel goes down and is activated when X homing ; no need to add an extra gcode for this.
    After homing X Y and Z a Z movement down lifts the dowel and re-arms for a next use. this movement need an extra gcode for XY positionning and for lower the hot-end.
    Two possibilities
  • Stick a coin or a button cell on the build plate (2 ou 3 mm) this will be the contact position for re-arms
  • while positioning the head outside the build plate area (y = 205 mm), this allow the nozzle to move under Z0 and the plate to lifts the dowel
    • for building this sensor we need :
    A microswitch 12.7 x 5.7mm, very common in computer mouse, this can be wired as NO or NC depending on your firmware

  • A bicycle spoke diam 2 mm cut to 75mm, keep the thread for fixing the head button

  • A spring like those found in pens

  • An electrical connection block for maintening the sping on the spoke

  • A piece of double side tape for maintening the arming stick

  • A piece of foam as lever spring
    • sample of gcode G28 X ; homing X and move down the probe sensor G28 Y G1 X100 Y100 F3000 G28 Z ; homing Z, needed before 4 points probing G92 Z0 G91 G1 Z5 ; move up 5 mm before 4 points probing G29; Detailed Z-Probe G92 Z10 G1 Z4 ; move up over the coin or button cell G90 G1 X10 Y120 ; move over the coin or button cell G91 ; mode relatif G1 Z-5.2 ; move down the hot-end for fixing Z0 and lifts the probe sensor G90 G92 Z0 ; set Z to zero G91 G1 Z8 F3000 ; move up to 8 mm if you encounter an issue to go below Z0, you must probably modify your firmware and increase the Z offset like this
    define Z_PROBE_OFFSET_FROM_EXTRUDER -10 https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=e5EaKH_T2fQ&feature=youtu.be

description.text: Here is my new Easy feed Extruder. The goal of the design is to change filament quickly. At the moment I'm doing my first tests with it. So there will change some details in the next days. As axis for the filament transport I use an 55 mm long M5 threaded rod with a modified M5 expansion anchor, which is fixed with two M5 Nuts. There are 3 ball bearings 5-625 inside. Two for the axis and one to press against the filament. When it is running fine I start to develop an automatic filament changer for this extruder. It fits optimal on this K8200 mod: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:713098 I changed the steps for the extruder to 370 in this configuration. It is working fine. Now I will make my experience with it and make it better and better... I'm sorry for the bad photo quality, but I a have a phone with a real bad camra. I'm able to change filament while printing as you can see on one of the photos.
